ws |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/stewart-s-melville-19-64-watson-s-hoffie-is-star-of-u16-final-1-4632835 |title=Stewart\u2019s Melville 19 - 64 Watson\u2019s: Hoffie is star of U16 final |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=6 December 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018-19 || [[George Watson's College]] || 15-5 || [[High School of Dundee]]<ref name=\"201819 u16 final\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/george-watsons-15-5-hs-of-dundee-watson-s-retain-u16-cup-1-4839992 |title=George Watsons 15-5 HS of Dundee: Watson\u2019s retain U16 Cup |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=5 December 2018 |accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019-20 || [[Merchiston Castle School]] || 41-5 || [[Dollar Academy]]<ref name=\"201920 u16 final\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/dollar-academy-5-41-merchiston-capital-youngsters-power-to-u16-cup-glory-1-5057165 |title=Dollar Academy 5 - 41 Merchiston: Capital youngsters power to U16 Cup glory |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=4 December 2019 |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==Scotland internationalists==\nA number of full Scotland internationalists have played in the schools' cup.  Some of whom are listed below:\n\n*[[John Barclay (rugby union)|John Barclay]]<ref name=\"john barclay\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby/top_rugby_stories/barclay_symbolises_strength_of_dollar_1_512685 |title=Barclay symbolises strength of Dollar |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=6 February 2004 |accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Alasdair Dickinson]]<ref name=\"graeme morrison\" />\n*[[Phil Godman]]<ref name=\"phil godman\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/stewart_s_melville_v_edinburgh_academy_godman_recalls_fond_memories_as_schools_gear_up_for_brewin_final_1_1503934 |title=Stewart's Melville v Edinburgh Academy: Godman recalls fond memories as schools gear up for Brewin final |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Ruaridh Jackson]]<ref name=\"ruaridh jackson\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotlandrugbyteam.org/content/view/208/86/ |title=Scotland Squad |publisher=Scottish Rugby |year=2012 |accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Graeme Morrison]]<ref name=\"graeme morrison\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby/top_rugby_stories/dollar_crash_to_on_form_fettes_in_cup_thriller_1_524198 |title=Dollar crash to on-form Fettes in cup thriller |newspaper=The Scotsman |date=8 March 2001 |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Gregor Townsend]]<ref name=\"1989 final\" />\n*[[Richie Vernon]]<ref name=\"richie vernon\">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/2354412/Dundees-tall-order-to-halt-top-Dollar.html |title=Dundee's tall order to halt top Dollar |publisher=The Daily Telegraph (London) |date=27 January 2005 |accessdate=3 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.schoolsrugby.co.uk/ Schools Rugby website]\n* [http://www.scottishrugby.org/schools-cup-competitions-201718 Scottish Rugby website]\n\n{{Rugby union in Scotland}}\n\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1983]]\n[[Category:School sport in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Rugby union competitions in Scotland|Schools' Cup]]\n", "name_user": "Davyc78", "label": "safe", "comment": "Peebles High School link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scottish_Rugby_Schools%27_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Emery Lehman", "text_new": "{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Emery Lehman\n| full_name      = Emery Chance Lehman\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1996|6|13}}\n| birth_place    = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| residence      = [[Oak Park, Illinois]]\n| height         = {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m}}<ref name=profile />\n| weight         = {{convert|167|lb|kg}}<ref name=profile />\n| alma_mater     = [[Marquette University]]\n| website        = \n| country        = {{USA}}\n| coach          = Eric Cepuran\n| club =  Franklin Park Speedskating Club\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[speed skating]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|the {{USA}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|Junior World Championships}}\n{{Medal|Gold|2013 Collalbo|5000 m}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2014 Bjugn|5000 m}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2014 Bjugn|Allround}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2015 Warsaw|1500 m}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2015 Warsaw|5000 m}}\n}}\n\n'''Emery Chance Lehman''' (born June 13, 1996) is an American [[speed skater]] who represented the United States at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] and the [[2018 Winter Olympics]].  Lehman started playing [[ice hockey]] at age six, taking up speed skating in an attempt to improve his hockey at age nine.  He excelled at the sport, winning his first national time at age 12.  Two years later, he won the US junior title in the 5000 meters.  The next year, he won four junior national titles.\n\nLehman won the senior 2012\u201313 National Championship in the 5000 meters and three titles at the junior championships. He then won a gold and a bronze medal at the [[ISU Junior World Cup Speed Skating|World Junior Championships]].  In his senior year of high school, Lehman won the 10000 meters at the 2013\u201314 US Senior Championship/Olympic Trials, and took second place in the 5000 meters.  At the Olympics, he placed 16th in the 5000 meters, and 10th in the 10000 meters.\n\nAs of 2014, Lehman held three national junior speed skating records.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nLehman was born in [[Chicago]], Illinois, to parents Marcia and David, and is Jewish.<ref name=Sochi2014 /><ref name=prepare /><ref>Ari Feldman (February 7, 2018). [https://forward.com/fast-forward/393843/meet-the-jews-going-to-the-winter-olympics-in-south-korea/ \"Meet The Jews Going To The Winter Olympics In South Korea,\"] ''The Forward''.</ref> His mother works in Chicago for [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]], and his father works for himself.<ref name=wj>[http://waterjoe.com/emerylehman/ \"#teamjoe Athlete \u2013 Emery Lehman\"], http://waterjoe.com.</ref> He lives in [[Oak Park, Illinois]].<ref name=wj/>  As of 2014, he was a senior at [[Oak Park and River Forest High School]], where he was an honor student.<ref name=profile /><ref name=second />  He was studying to become an engineer.<ref name=prepare />\n\nDuring his time off, Lehman enjoys playing [[table tennis]] with friends.<ref name=prepare /> He volunteers regularly at the Oak Park River Forest Food Pantry, and is in the process of being certified as a speed skating coach.<ref name=profile />  Lehman lists the [[Chicago Bears]] and [[Chicago Blackhawks]] as his favorite sports teams, and [[Bo Jackson]] as his sporting hero.<ref name=Sochi2014 /><ref name=earns>{{cite news|title=High schooler Emery Lehman earns Olympic berth |author=Beth Harris |date=December 28, 2013 |agency=AP |work=The Wichita Eagle |url=http://www.kansas.com/2013/12/28/3199759/high-schooler-emery-lehman-earns.html |accessdate=January 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104210923/http://www.kansas.com/2013/12/28/3199759/high-schooler-emery-lehman-earns.html |archivedate=January 4, 2014 }}</ref>  He says his mother has been the most influential person in his life.<ref name=Sochi2014 />\n\nEmery is currently a student at [[Marquette University]] majoring in [[Civil Engineering]].\n\n==Athletic career==\n\n===Ice hockey===\nLehman began playing [[ice hockey]] when he was six years old.  As a sophomore in high school, he was selected as a conference All-Star playing defense for [[Oak Park and River Forest High School]]'s (OPRF) varsity team.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|title=Emery Lehman: US Speedskating|publisher=Team USA|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/LE/Emery-Lehman|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  Describing Lehman's game, his coach remarked, \"He delivers absolute monster hits&nbsp;... He doesn't get knocked down, and he is always first to the puck\".<ref name=ahead />  During the summer of 2013, Lehman hurt his ankle and the new OPRF hockey coach did not want to play him for fear of an injury jeopardizing Lehman's Olympic speed skating chances.<ref name=speeding /> Lehman thus took his senior year off from hockey.<ref name=earns /> Emery Lehman reignited his career with Marquette\u2019s ACHA Division II Hockey Team. He played defense for the team, scoring 2 goals and 10 assists while meeting his best friend Senior, Michael DeSalvo. His linemate was senior Colin Redman (better known as the brother of the four star TE, Mark Redman)\n\n===Speed skating===\nAt age nine, Lehman saw a poster claiming speed skating could help improve hockey skills.  His mother persuaded Lehman to give it a try and he found he had a talent for the sport.<ref name=drive>{{cite news|title=Oak Park teen a driven and determined speed skater|author=Brad Spencer|date=February 21, 2012|work=Wednesday Journal|url=http://www.oakpark.com/News/Articles/2-21-2012/Oak-Park-teen-a-driven-and-determined-speed-skater/|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLehman was a 2008\u201309 [[short track speed skating|short]] and [[long track speed skating]] national champion. In 2010, Emery began training with 2x Olympian Jeff Klaiber (who would coach Emery at the Olympic Games and through the 2015-16 season). In 2010-11, Emery won the 5000 meters at the 2010\u201311 United States Junior Championships, and was third in the All-Around.  He participated in the 2010\u201311 World Junior Championships, placing 11th in the 5000 meters and 18th in the All-Around, at age 14.  At the 2011\u201312 US Junior Championships, Lehman won the 1500 meter, 3000 meter, and 5000 meter distances, and also placed first in the All-Around.<ref name=profile />  In his second year at the World Junior Championships, he was the youngest competitor in the field.<ref name=ahead />  At the senior National Championships that year, he placed sixth in the 1500 meter and 5000 meter events.  He was fifth in the All-Around.<ref name=profile />\n\nAt the 2012 World Cup trials, Lehman improved his personal best in the 5000 meters by ten seconds, to 6:28.56.  Aged 16, he became the youngest skater ever to break 6:30.  He finished second overall and qualified for the senior World Cup team. \"I know I'm doing well, but I didn't know it would be this well,\" Lehman remarked.<ref name=ahead>{{cite news|title=Precocious speedskater ahead of his time|date=November 15, 2012|author=Philip Hersh|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-11-15/sports/ct-spt-1116-hersh-speed-skating--20121116_1_hockey-team-winter-olympic-strong-contender|accessdate=January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2012\u201313 US National Championships, he again improved his 5000-meter time, winning  with a time of 6:27.06.  He also took part in the 500, 1000, 1500, and 10000 meter events.  He turned in personal best times in all four events and placed third in the 10000 meters.<ref name=results />  At the US Junior Championships, Lehman won the 1500, 3000, and 5000 meter events.  At the World Junior Championships, he won a bronze medal in the 3000 meters, and a gold medal in the 5000 meters with a time of 6:38.76. At the senior World Championships, he placed 20th in the 5000 meters.<ref name=results />\n\nIn November 2013, Lehman improved his own Junior National Record and came within 0.8 seconds of the World Junior record with a time of 6:19.87 in the 5000 meters.<ref name=speeding>{{cite news|title=Emery Lehman speeding toward Olympic Trials|work=Chicago Sun-Times|author=Rich Martin|date=November 19, 2013|url=http://www.highschoolcubenews.com/news_article/show/311459|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  On December 27, Lehman, skating in the last of 10 pairs of athletes, completed the 5000 meters in a time of 6:25.90 at the US Olympic Trials.  The time placed him second and qualified Lehman for his first Olympic Games.<ref name=earns />\n\nOn January 1, 2014, Lehman took part in the 10000 meter race at the Olympic Trials.  With three laps to go, he was four seconds behind 2010 Olympian [[Jonathan Kuck]].  Lehman took the lead with one lap to go.  Kuck re-took the lead at the final turn, but Lehman edged him by seven hundredths of a second, about two blade lengths, at the finish line. \"That was pretty insane,\" remarked Lehman. \"I didn't expect to be finishing anywhere close to Jonathan.\"<ref name=second>{{cite news|title=U.S. teen earns second Olympic event at speedskating trials|work=USA Today|agency=AP|date=January 1, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/2014/01/01/emery-lehman-earns-second-sochi-olympics-event-usa-speedskating-trials/4282535/|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  Lehman's time of 13:22.77 improved his personal best by seven seconds,<ref name=second/> and placed him first overall with one pairing \u2013 [[Patrick Meek]] and Edwin Park \u2013 remaining. Meek finished 0.39 seconds behind Lehman, taking third.<ref name=second /> Gary D'Amato of the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'' called the race \"perhaps the most thrilling race of the trials\".<ref name=from_behind>{{cite news|title=Emery Lehman comes from behind to win 10,000-meter race|author=Gary D'Amato|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=January 1, 2014|url=http://www.jsonline.com/sports/emery-lehman-comes-from-behind-to-win-10000-meter-race-b99175497z1-238399351.html|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the Olympics, Lehman placed 16th in the 5000 meters with a time of 6:29.94.<ref name=Sochi2014>{{cite web|title=Athletes: Emery Lehman|work=Sochi 2014|url=http://www.sochi2014.com/en/athlete-emery-lehman|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref>  He was the top finishing American. Later, he placed 10th in the 10000 meters with a time of 13:28.67, far exceeding his personal best for a race at [[sea level]].  The exertion of the race caused him to vomit.  After the games, he went directly to the World Junior Championships.<ref name=prepare>{{cite news|title=Friends, family prepare to welcome home Oak Park Olympian|author=Wes Venteicher|date=February 25, 2014|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-02-25/news/ct-emery-lehman-oak-park-tl-0227-20140225_1_marcia-lehman-emery-lehman-sochi|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLehman trains at the [[Pettit National Ice Center]], and is coached by Eric Cepuran. He is a member of the Franklin Park Speedskating Club.<ref name=profile />\n\nLehman was named Team Pursuit Specialist for the 2018 Winter Olympics. He is the 5k 2018 National Champion, and gained an Olympic spot to skate for Team USA at the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang. He placed 21st in the 5,000 meters by finishing in 6 minutes, 31.16 seconds.<ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/oak-park/sports/ct-oak-emery-lehman-speed-skating-5000-meters-tl-0211-20180211-story.html \"Oak Park speed skater Emery Lehman places 21st in Olympic 5,000 meters\" - Oak Leaves<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He and the Team USA team pursuit trio, which also included [[Brian Hansen (speed skater)|Brian Hansen]] and [[Joey Mantia]], finished in eighth place in the D final, with a time of 3:50.77, after skating 3:42.98 in the prior round.<ref>[https://marquettewire.org/3987676/sports/lehman-finishes-up-olympics-with-eighth-place-finish-in-team-pursuit-event/ \"Lehman finishes Olympics with eighth place finish in team pursuit\" \u2013 ''Marquette Wire''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/international/ct-spt-olympics-team-pursuit-speedskating-20180218-story.html \"South Koreans, Dutch lead team pursuit; Team USA last\" - ''Chicago Tribune''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Lacrosse===\nLehman also plays [[lacrosse]] competitively, serving as a midfielder.<ref name=ahead />  During the summers, he plays on an elite travel team in Illinois.  As a freshman in high school, he was the team captain.<ref name=profile />  Lehman's coach says he is a \"very skilled player\" who could play for a \"high-level Division III to mid-level Division I\" college program.<ref name=ahead /> He is a member of Marquette's Club Lacrosse team in his off season to stay in shape.\n\n==Personal bests==\n{{PersonalRecordsTop|ref=<ref name=results>{{cite web|url = http://www.speedskatingresults.com/index.php?p=17&s=14959|title = Emery Lehman|publisher  = SpeedSkatingResults.com|accessdate = October 18, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsSport|Men's speed skating}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|500 m|36.78|March 18, 2017|[[Calgary Olympic Oval]], Calgary|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1000 m|1:10.90|January 3, 2018|Pettit National Ice Center, Milwaukee|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1500 m|1:44.95|December 29, 2019|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|3000 m|3:46.09|August 26, 2017|[[Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City]] |<ref name=njr>{{cite web|url = http://www.speedskatingresults.com/index.php?p=11|title = National Records \u2013 United States (USA) |publisher  = SpeedSkatingResults.com|accessdate = October 18, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|5000 m|6:18.03|December 1, 2017|Calgary Olympic Oval, Calgary|<ref name=njr/>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|10000 m|13:22.77|January 1, 2014|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|<ref name=njr/>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsBottom}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jews in sports#Speed Skating|List of select Jewish speed skaters]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{USOPC profile}}\n* {{IOC profile}}\n* {{SR/Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lehman, Emery}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male speed skaters]]\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of the United States]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 2018 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Oak Park, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Marquette University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = Emery Lehman\n| full_name      = Emery Chance Lehman\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1996|6|13}}\n| birth_place    = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| residence      = [[Oak Park, Illinois]]\n| height         = {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m}}<ref name=profile />\n| weight         = {{convert|167|lb|kg}}<ref name=profile />\n| alma_mater     = [[Marquette University]]\n| website        = \n| country        = {{USA}}\n| coach          = Eric Cepuran\n| club =  Franklin Park Speedskating Club\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[speed skating]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|the {{USA}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|Junior World Championships}}\n{{Medal|Gold|2013 Collalbo|5000 m}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2014 Bjugn|5000 m}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2014 Bjugn|Allround}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2015 Warsaw|1500 m}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2015 Warsaw|5000 m}}\n}}\n'''Emery Chance Lehman''' (born June 13, 1996) is an American [[speed skater]] who represented the United States at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] and the [[2018 Winter Olympics]].  Lehman started playing [[ice hockey]] at age six, taking up speed skating in an attempt to improve his hockey at age nine.  He excelled at the sport, winning his first national time at age 12.  Two years later, he won the US junior title in the 5000 meters.  The next year, he won four junior national titles.\n\nLehman won the senior 2012\u201313 National Championship in the 5000 meters and three titles at the junior championships. He then won a gold and a bronze medal at the [[ISU Junior World Cup Speed Skating|World Junior Championships]].  In his senior year of high school, Lehman won the 10000 meters at the 2013\u201314 US Senior Championship/Olympic Trials, and took second place in the 5000 meters.  At the Olympics, he placed 16th in the 5000 meters, and 10th in the 10000 meters.\n\nAs of 2014, Lehman held three national junior speed skating records.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nLehman was born in [[Chicago]], Illinois, to parents Marcia and David, and is Jewish.<ref name=Sochi2014 /><ref name=prepare /><ref>Ari Feldman (February 7, 2018). [https://forward.com/fast-forward/393843/meet-the-jews-going-to-the-winter-olympics-in-south-korea/ \"Meet The Jews Going To The Winter Olympics In South Korea,\"] ''The Forward''.</ref> His mother works in Chicago for [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]], and his father works for himself.<ref name=wj>[http://waterjoe.com/emerylehman/ \"#teamjoe Athlete \u2013 Emery Lehman\"], http://waterjoe.com.</ref> He lives in [[Oak Park, Illinois]].<ref name=wj/>  As of 2014, he was a senior at [[Oak Park and River Forest High School]], where he was an honor student.<ref name=profile /><ref name=second />  He was studying to become an engineer.<ref name=prepare />\n\nDuring his time off, Lehman enjoys playing [[table tennis]] with friends.<ref name=prepare /> He volunteers regularly at the Oak Park River Forest Food Pantry, and is in the process of being certified as a speed skating coach.<ref name=profile />  Lehman lists the [[Chicago Bears]] and [[Chicago Blackhawks]] as his favorite sports teams, and [[Bo Jackson]] as his sporting hero.<ref name=Sochi2014 /><ref name=earns>{{cite news|title=High schooler Emery Lehman earns Olympic berth |author=Beth Harris |date=December 28, 2013 |agency=AP |work=The Wichita Eagle |url=http://www.kansas.com/2013/12/28/3199759/high-schooler-emery-lehman-earns.html |accessdate=January 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104210923/http://www.kansas.com/2013/12/28/3199759/high-schooler-emery-lehman-earns.html |archivedate=January 4, 2014 }}</ref>  He says his mother has been the most influential person in his life.<ref name=Sochi2014 />\n\nEmery is currently a student at [[Marquette University]] majoring in [[Civil Engineering]].\n\n==Athletic career==\n\n===Ice hockey===\nLehman began playing [[ice hockey]] when he was six years old.  As a sophomore in high school, he was selected as a conference All-Star playing defense for [[Oak Park and River Forest High School]]'s (OPRF) varsity team.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|title=Emery Lehman: US Speedskating|publisher=Team USA|url=http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/LE/Emery-Lehman|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  Describing Lehman's game, his coach remarked, \"He delivers absolute monster hits&nbsp;... He doesn't get knocked down, and he is always first to the puck\".<ref name=ahead />  During the summer of 2013, Lehman hurt his ankle and the new OPRF hockey coach did not want to play him for fear of an injury jeopardizing Lehman's Olympic speed skating chances.<ref name=speeding /> Lehman thus took his senior year off from hockey.<ref name=earns /> Emery Lehman reignited his career with Marquette\u2019s ACHA Division II Hockey Team. He played defense for the team, scoring 2 goals and 10 assists while meeting his best friend Senior, Michael DeSalvo. His linemate was senior Colin Redman (better known as the brother of the four star TE, Mark Redman)\n\n===Speed skating===\nAt age nine, Lehman saw a poster claiming speed skating could help improve hockey skills.  His mother persuaded Lehman to give it a try and he found he had a talent for the sport.<ref name=drive>{{cite news|title=Oak Park teen a driven and determined speed skater|author=Brad Spencer|date=February 21, 2012|work=Wednesday Journal|url=http://www.oakpark.com/News/Articles/2-21-2012/Oak-Park-teen-a-driven-and-determined-speed-skater/|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLehman was a 2008\u201309 [[short track speed skating|short]] and [[long track speed skating]] national champion. In 2010, Emery began training with 2x Olympian Jeff Klaiber (who would coach Emery at the Olympic Games and through the 2015-16 season). In 2010-11, Emery won the 5000 meters at the 2010\u201311 United States Junior Championships, and was third in the All-Around.  He participated in the 2010\u201311 World Junior Championships, placing 11th in the 5000 meters and 18th in the All-Around, at age 14.  At the 2011\u201312 US Junior Championships, Lehman won the 1500 meter, 3000 meter, and 5000 meter distances, and also placed first in the All-Around.<ref name=profile />  In his second year at the World Junior Championships, he was the youngest competitor in the field.<ref name=ahead />  At the senior National Championships that year, he placed sixth in the 1500 meter and 5000 meter events.  He was fifth in the All-Around.<ref name=profile />\n\nAt the 2012 World Cup trials, Lehman improved his personal best in the 5000 meters by ten seconds, to 6:28.56.  Aged 16, he became the youngest skater ever to break 6:30.  He finished second overall and qualified for the senior World Cup team. \"I know I'm doing well, but I didn't know it would be this well,\" Lehman remarked.<ref name=ahead>{{cite news|title=Precocious speedskater ahead of his time|date=November 15, 2012|author=Philip Hersh|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-11-15/sports/ct-spt-1116-hersh-speed-skating--20121116_1_hockey-team-winter-olympic-strong-contender|accessdate=January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2012\u201313 US National Championships, he again improved his 5000-meter time, winning  with a time of 6:27.06.  He also took part in the 500, 1000, 1500, and 10000 meter events.  He turned in personal best times in all four events and placed third in the 10000 meters.<ref name=results />  At the US Junior Championships, Lehman won the 1500, 3000, and 5000 meter events.  At the World Junior Championships, he won a bronze medal in the 3000 meters, and a gold medal in the 5000 meters with a time of 6:38.76. At the senior World Championships, he placed 20th in the 5000 meters.<ref name=results />\n\nIn November 2013, Lehman improved his own Junior National Record and came within 0.8 seconds of the World Junior record with a time of 6:19.87 in the 5000 meters.<ref name=speeding>{{cite news|title=Emery Lehman speeding toward Olympic Trials|work=Chicago Sun-Times|author=Rich Martin|date=November 19, 2013|url=http://www.highschoolcubenews.com/news_article/show/311459|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  On December 27, Lehman, skating in the last of 10 pairs of athletes, completed the 5000 meters in a time of 6:25.90 at the US Olympic Trials.  The time placed him second and qualified Lehman for his first Olympic Games.<ref name=earns />\n\nOn January 1, 2014, Lehman took part in the 10000 meter race at the Olympic Trials.  With three laps to go, he was four seconds behind 2010 Olympian [[Jonathan Kuck]].  Lehman took the lead with one lap to go.  Kuck re-took the lead at the final turn, but Lehman edged him by seven hundredths of a second, about two blade lengths, at the finish line. \"That was pretty insane,\" remarked Lehman. \"I didn't expect to be finishing anywhere close to Jonathan.\"<ref name=second>{{cite news|title=U.S. teen earns second Olympic event at speedskating trials|work=USA Today|agency=AP|date=January 1, 2014|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/2014/01/01/emery-lehman-earns-second-sochi-olympics-event-usa-speedskating-trials/4282535/|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref>  Lehman's time of 13:22.77 improved his personal best by seven seconds,<ref name=second/> and placed him first overall with one pairing \u2013 [[Patrick Meek]] and Edwin Park \u2013 remaining. Meek finished 0.39 seconds behind Lehman, taking third.<ref name=second /> Gary D'Amato of the ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'' called the race \"perhaps the most thrilling race of the trials\".<ref name=from_behind>{{cite news|title=Emery Lehman comes from behind to win 10,000-meter race|author=Gary D'Amato|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|date=January 1, 2014|url=http://www.jsonline.com/sports/emery-lehman-comes-from-behind-to-win-10000-meter-race-b99175497z1-238399351.html|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the Olympics, Lehman placed 16th in the 5000 meters with a time of 6:29.94.<ref name=Sochi2014>{{cite web|title=Athletes: Emery Lehman|work=Sochi 2014|url=http://www.sochi2014.com/en/athlete-emery-lehman|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref>  He was the top finishing American. Later, he placed 10th in the 10000 meters with a time of 13:28.67, far exceeding his personal best for a race at [[sea level]].  The exertion of the race caused him to vomit.  After the games, he went directly to the World Junior Championships.<ref name=prepare>{{cite news|title=Friends, family prepare to welcome home Oak Park Olympian|author=Wes Venteicher|date=February 25, 2014|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-02-25/news/ct-emery-lehman-oak-park-tl-0227-20140225_1_marcia-lehman-emery-lehman-sochi|accessdate=March 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLehman trains at the [[Pettit National Ice Center]], and is coached by Eric Cepuran. He is a member of the Franklin Park Speedskating Club.<ref name=profile />\n\nLehman was named Team Pursuit Specialist for the 2018 Winter Olympics. He is the 5k 2018 National Champion, and gained an Olympic spot to skate for Team USA at the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang. He placed 21st in the 5,000 meters by finishing in 6 minutes, 31.16 seconds.<ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/oak-park/sports/ct-oak-emery-lehman-speed-skating-5000-meters-tl-0211-20180211-story.html \"Oak Park speed skater Emery Lehman places 21st in Olympic 5,000 meters\" - Oak Leaves<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He and the Team USA team pursuit trio, which also included [[Brian Hansen (speed skater)|Brian Hansen]] and [[Joey Mantia]], finished in eighth place in the D final, with a time of 3:50.77, after skating 3:42.98 in the prior round.<ref>[https://marquettewire.org/3987676/sports/lehman-finishes-up-olympics-with-eighth-place-finish-in-team-pursuit-event/ \"Lehman finishes Olympics with eighth place finish in team pursuit\" \u2013 ''Marquette Wire''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/international/ct-spt-olympics-team-pursuit-speedskating-20180218-story.html \"South Koreans, Dutch lead team pursuit; Team USA last\" - ''Chicago Tribune''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Lacrosse===\nLehman also plays [[lacrosse]] competitively, serving as a midfielder.<ref name=ahead />  During the summers, he plays on an elite travel team in Illinois.  As a freshman in high school, he was the team captain.<ref name=profile />  Lehman's coach says he is a \"very skilled player\" who could play for a \"high-level Division III to mid-level Division I\" college program.<ref name=ahead /> He is a member of Marquette's Club Lacrosse team in his off season to stay in shape.\n\n==Personal bests==\n{{PersonalRecordsTop|ref=<ref name=results>{{cite web|url = http://www.speedskatingresults.com/index.php?p=17&s=14959|title = Emery Lehman|publisher  = SpeedSkatingResults.com|accessdate = October 18, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsSport|Men's speed skating}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|500 m|36.78|March 18, 2017|[[Calgary Olympic Oval]], Calgary|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1000 m|1:10.90|January 3, 2018|Pettit National Ice Center, Milwaukee|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1500 m|1:44.95|December 29, 2019|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|3000 m|3:46.09|August 26, 2017|[[Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City]] |<ref name=njr>{{cite web|url = http://www.speedskatingresults.com/index.php?p=11|title = National Records \u2013 United States (USA) |publisher  = SpeedSkatingResults.com|accessdate = October 18, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|5000 m|6:18.03|December 1, 2017|Calgary Olympic Oval, Calgary|<ref name=njr/>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|10000 m|13:22.77|January 1, 2014|Utah Olympic Oval, Salt Lake City|<ref name=njr/>}}\n{{PersonalRecordsBottom}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jews in sports#Speed Skating|List of select Jewish speed skaters]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.teamusa.org/Athletes/LE/Emery-Lehman Official profile] at Team USA website\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lehman, Emery}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male speed skaters]]\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of the United States]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 2018 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Oak Park, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Marquette University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "use template for USOPC link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emery_Lehman"}
{"title_page": "Dzyarzhynsk", "text_new": "{{about|the Belarusian city|other cities with similar names|Dzerzhinsk (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type     = City\n|name=Dzyarzhynsk\n|other_name=\n|native_name = {{native name|be|\u0414\u0437\u044f\u0440\u0436\u044b\u043d\u0441\u043a|italics=off}}<br/>{{native name|ru|\u0414\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a|italics=off}}\n|nickname           = \n|image_skyline      =\n|image_size          = \n|image_caption       =\n|image_flag         = Flag of Dziar\u017eynsk, Belarus.svg\n|image_shield       = Coat of Arms of Dziar\u017eynsk, Belarus.svg\n|image_map          = \n|map_caption        = \n|pushpin_map=Belarus\n|subdivision_type   = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name   = {{flag|Belarus}}\n|subdivision_type1=[[Voblast]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[Minsk Region]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Raion]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[Dzyarzhynsk District]]\n|leader_title       = \n|leader_name        = \n|established_title  = Founded\n|established_date   = 1146\n|area_magnitude     = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|area_land_km2          = \n|area_water_km2         = \n|population_as_of   = 2009\n|population_footnotes = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-43&srt=npan&col=abcdefghinoq&msz=1500&pt=c&va=&srt=pnan|title=Belarus: largest cities and towns and statistics of their population|publisher=World Gazetteer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130111110701/http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-43&srt=npan&col=abcdefghinoq&msz=1500&pt=c&va=&srt=pnan|archivedate=January 11, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> \n|population_total   =25164\n|population_metro   = \n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|timezone           = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset         = +2\n|timezone_DST       = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST     = +3\n|coordinates        = {{coord|53|41|00|N|27|08|00|E|region:BY|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m        = \n|postal_code_type   = Postal code\n|postal_code        = 222720\n|area_code          = +375 1716\n|blank_name         = License plate \n|blank_info         = 5\n|website            = [http://www.dzerzhinsk.minsk-region.by/ Official website]\n|footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Dzyarzhynsk''' or '''Dzerzhinsk''', formerly '''Koidanova''' or '''Koydanava''' ({{lang-be|\u0414\u0437\u044f\u0440\u0436\u044b\u0301\u043d\u0441\u043a|Dziar\u017eynsk}}, formerly {{lang|be|\u041a\u043e\u0301\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0430}}, {{small|romanized:}} {{transl|be|Kojdanava}}; {{lang-ru|\u0414\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0438\u0301\u043d\u0441\u043a|Dzerzhinsk}}, formerly {{lang|ru|\u041a\u043e\u0301\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0430}}, {{small|romanized:}} {{transl|ru|Koydanova}}; {{lang-pl|Kojdan\u00f3w}}; {{lang-yi|\u05e7\u05d5\u05d9\u05d3\u05e0\u05d5\u05d1|Koidanov}}; {{lang-lt|Kaidanava}}), in the [[Dzyarzhynsk District]] of [[Belarus]], is a city with a history dating to the 11th century. \n==History==\nIn the [[Middle Ages]], the village belonged to the [[Radziwi\u0142\u0142]]s, a [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Polish-Lithuanian]] aristocratic family.  Jews lived in Koidanova as early as 1620.<ref name=\"beljews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beljews.info/Koidanova.htm |title=Koidanova |publisher=Beljews.info |date= |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Jewish community===\n\nJews lived in Koidanova as early as 1620.<ref name=\"beljews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beljews.info/Koidanova.htm |title=Koidanova |publisher=Beljews.info |date= |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> Koidanova became the site of a new [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] [[Jews|Jewish]] [[List of Hasidic dynasties|dynasty]] in 1833 when Rabbi Shlomo Chaim Perlow (1797\u20131862) became the first Koidanover [[Rebbe]].<ref name=\"gen\">{{cite web|url=http://kehilalinks.jewishgen.org/lyakhovichi/rabbonim.htm|title=Rabbonim, Rebbes, and Crown Rabbis, of Lyakhovichi|first=Deborah G.|last=Glassman|year=2004|publisher=[[JewishGen]]|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> He was succeeded by his son, Rabbi Boruch Mordechai Perlow (1818&ndash;1870), grandson, Rabbi [[Aharon Perlow of Koidanov|Aharon Perlow]] (1839&ndash;1897), and great-grandson, Rabbi Yosef Perlow of Koidanov-[[Minsk]] (1854-1915), who was the last Koidanover Rebbe to live in the town. After World War I, the dynasty was moved to [[Baranovichi]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|year=2010|publisher=The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe|first=Allen|last=Nadler|url=http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Koidanov_Hasidic_Dynasty|title=Koidanov Hasidic Dynasty|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1847, Koidanova had 2,497 Jewish inhabitants.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>  In 1897 the city had a total population of 4,744, of whom 3,156 were Jews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beljews.info/Minsk1.htm|title=Jewish population of Minsk uezd according to the 1897 Russian Census|publisher=beljews.info|date=|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Inter-war period===\n[[File:Kojdana\u016d. \u041a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u045e (1932).jpg|thumb|The People's House in Dzyarzhynsk, capital of the ''Dzier\u017cy\u0144szczyzna'', in 1932]]\nIn May 1932 it was granted the status of a city and was renamed '''Kojdana\u016d''' ({{lang-be|\u041a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u045e}}), Russian: '''Koidanov'''.  In June of that year it was renamed again as Dziar\u017eynsk by the [[Communism|Communist]] authorities, in honour of [[Felix Dzerzhinsky]] (1877\u20131926), a famous Bolshevik creator and chief of the \"Cherezzychainaya Komissija\" ([[CHEKA]]) \u2013 the Soviet secret police - who was born in a Dziar\u017eynava estate not far from the city, although on the other side of the then Polish-Soviet border.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>\n\nThe city was the capital of the short-lived [[Dzierzynszczyzna]] [[Polish Autonomous District]] during 1932\u201338.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>\n\n===World War II===\nIt fell under [[Operation Barbarossa|German occupation]] during World War II. It was captured on June 28, 1941.\n\nThe [[Lithuania]]n Twelfth [[Schutzmannschaft]] (auxiliary police) Battalion's 1st Company, led by Lieutenant Z. Kemzura, massacred approximately 1,600 Jews from the city on October 21, 1941, shooting them and throwing them into a pit; many were buried alive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jhrgbelarus.org/Heritage_Holocaust.php?pid=&lang=en&city_id=8&type=3|title=Jewish Heritage Research Group in Belarus|publisher=Jhrgbelarus.org|date=October 21, 1941|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Richard|last=Breitman|authorlink=Richard Breitman|url=https://motlc.wiesenthal.com/site/pp.asp?c=gvKVLcMVIuG&b=395183|title=Himmler's Police Auxiliaries in the Occupied Soviet Territories|publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Center Multimedia Learning Center|date=1997|accessdate=August 20, 2011|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727011820/http://motlc.wiesenthal.com/site/pp.asp?c=gvKVLcMVIuG&b=395183|archivedate=July 27, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"google1941\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wvyX6Vjkq3MC&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=Koidanov+1941+-mascot#PPA155,M1 |title=The Complete Black Book of Russian Jewry |publisher= |author= |date=June 13, 2003 |accessdate=August 20, 2011|isbn=9781412820073 |author1=Patterson |first1=David }}</ref>  As it is reported in ''The Complete Black Book of Russian Jewry'': \"For three hours the earth covering the mass grave would move; people still alive were trying to crawl out of their grave.\"<ref name=\"google1941\"/>  On March 1\u20132,1942, the [[Einsatzgruppen]] transported several thousand Jews from throughout Belarussia and murdered them in Koidanov.<ref>{{cite book |author=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |title=Historical Atlas of the Holocaust |publisher=Macmillan / Simon & Schuster |date=1995 |isbn=978-0028974514 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/historicalatlaso00unit }} See in [https://www.rtrfoundation.org/map11a.shtml Routes to Roots Foundation, Inc.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821104558/https://www.rtrfoundation.org/map11a.shtml |date=August 21, 2016 }}</ref> The city was liberated by the Soviet [[Red Army]] on July 6, 1944.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>\n\n===Modern day===\n[[File:Dzrerzhinsk Minsk oblast ulica Sovetskaja.jpg|thumb|Shopping centre in Dzyarzhynsk]]\n\nIn 1998, the city had 24,700 inhabitants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.populstat.info/Europe/belarust.htm |title=BELARUS: urban population |publisher=Populstat.info |date= |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNow part of Belarus, the name Kojdanava ({{lang-be|\u041a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0430}}) is becoming popular again (it is the official name for the [[railway station]] of Dziarzhynsk), but the official name remains unchanged.\n\n==Geography==\nThe highest point of Belarus, [[Dziar\u017eynskaja Hara]], is several kilometers from Dziar\u017eynsk.\n\n== Transport ==\nThere is a railway road across the city from [[Minsk Railway station|Minsk Passazhirsky]] to Baranovichi Polesskie.\n\nThere is only one bus route in Dziarzhynsk, that has 18 stops.\n\n==Notable residents==\n* \n*[[Avrom Reyzen]] (1876\u20131953), Yiddish writer, poet, and editor\n*[[Aharon Perlow of Koidanov|Aharon Perlow]] (1839&ndash;1897) &ndash; third [[rebbe]] of [[Koidanov (Hasidic dynasty)|Koidanov]]\n*[[Karol Hutten-Czapski]], [[Leliwa coat of arms]], (1860-1904).  [[Poles|Polish]] [[Count]] and philanthropist. President of [[Minsk]], [[Lithuania]] (1890-1901)\n*[[Emeryk Hutten-Czapski]], [[Leliwa coat of arms]], (1828\u20131896).  [[Poland|Polish]] [[Count]], scholar, ardent historical collector and [[numismatist]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Dziar\u017eynsk}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040402171314/http://www.dzerzhinsk.boom.ru/aboutme.html Dzerzhinsk (in Russian)]\n* [http://www.radzima.org/eng/town/dzyarzhynsk-koydanava.html Photos on Radzima.org]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050221025912/http://uk.multimap.com/wi/337941.htm Map of Dziar\u017eynsk]\n\n\n{{Minsk Voblast}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Minsk Region]]\n[[Category:Dzyarzhynsk District]]\n[[Category:Minsk Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Minsky Uyezd]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Belarusian city|other cities with similar names|Dzerzhinsk (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type     = City\n|name=Dzyarzhynsk\n|other_name=\n|native_name = {{native name|be|\u0414\u0437\u044f\u0440\u0436\u044b\u043d\u0441\u043a|italics=off}}<br/>{{native name|ru|\u0414\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a|italics=off}}\n|nickname           = \n|image_skyline      =\n|image_size          = \n|image_caption       =\n|image_flag         = Flag of Dziar\u017eynsk, Belarus.svg\n|image_shield       = Coat of Arms of Dziar\u017eynsk, Belarus.svg\n|image_map          = \n|map_caption        = \n|pushpin_map=Belarus\n|subdivision_type   = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name   = {{flag|Belarus}}\n|subdivision_type1=[[Voblast]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[Minsk Region]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Raion]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[Dzyarzhynsk District]]\n|leader_title       = \n|leader_name        = \n|established_title  = Founded\n|established_date   = 1146\n|area_magnitude     = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|area_land_km2          = \n|area_water_km2         = \n|population_as_of   = 2009\n|population_footnotes = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-43&srt=npan&col=abcdefghinoq&msz=1500&pt=c&va=&srt=pnan|title=Belarus: largest cities and towns and statistics of their population|publisher=World Gazetteer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130111110701/http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-43&srt=npan&col=abcdefghinoq&msz=1500&pt=c&va=&srt=pnan|archivedate=January 11, 2013|df=mdy}}</ref> \n|population_total   =25164\n|population_metro   = \n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|timezone           = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset         = +2\n|timezone_DST       = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST     = +3\n|coordinates        = {{coord|53|41|00|N|27|08|00|E|region:BY|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m        = \n|postal_code_type   = Postal code\n|postal_code        = 222720\n|area_code          = +375 1716\n|blank_name         = License plate \n|blank_info         = 5\n|website            = [http://www.dzerzhinsk.minsk-region.by/ Official website]\n|footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Dzyarzhynsk''' or '''Dzerzhinsk'''; formerly ''Koidanova'' or ''Koydanava'' ({{lang-be|\u0414\u0437\u044f\u0440\u0436\u044b\u0301\u043d\u0441\u043a}} ''Dziar\u017eynsk'' {{IPA-be|dz\u02b2ar\u02c8\u0290\u0268nsk|}}; {{lang-ru|\u0414\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0438\u0301\u043d\u0441\u043a}}, {{lang-pl|Kojdan\u00f3w}}; {{lang-yi|\u05e7\u05d5\u05d9\u05d3\u05e0\u05d5\u05d1}}, ''Koidanov'', {{lang-lt|Kaidanava}}), in the [[Dzyarzhynsk District]] of [[Belarus]], is a city with a history dating to the 11th century. \n==History==\nIn the [[Middle Ages]], the village belonged to the [[Radziwi\u0142\u0142]]s, a [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Polish-Lithuanian]] aristocratic family.  Jews lived in Koidanova as early as 1620.<ref name=\"beljews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beljews.info/Koidanova.htm |title=Koidanova |publisher=Beljews.info |date= |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Jewish community===\n\nJews lived in Koidanova as early as 1620.<ref name=\"beljews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beljews.info/Koidanova.htm |title=Koidanova |publisher=Beljews.info |date= |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref> Koidanova became the site of a new [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] [[Jews|Jewish]] [[List of Hasidic dynasties|dynasty]] in 1833 when Rabbi Shlomo Chaim Perlow (1797\u20131862) became the first Koidanover [[Rebbe]].<ref name=\"gen\">{{cite web|url=http://kehilalinks.jewishgen.org/lyakhovichi/rabbonim.htm|title=Rabbonim, Rebbes, and Crown Rabbis, of Lyakhovichi|first=Deborah G.|last=Glassman|year=2004|publisher=[[JewishGen]]|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> He was succeeded by his son, Rabbi Boruch Mordechai Perlow (1818&ndash;1870), grandson, Rabbi [[Aharon Perlow of Koidanov|Aharon Perlow]] (1839&ndash;1897), and great-grandson, Rabbi Yosef Perlow of Koidanov-[[Minsk]] (1854-1915), who was the last Koidanover Rebbe to live in the town. After World War I, the dynasty was moved to [[Baranovichi]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|year=2010|publisher=The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe|first=Allen|last=Nadler|url=http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Koidanov_Hasidic_Dynasty|title=Koidanov Hasidic Dynasty|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1847, Koidanova had 2,497 Jewish inhabitants.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>  In 1897 the city had a total population of 4,744, of whom 3,156 were Jews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beljews.info/Minsk1.htm|title=Jewish population of Minsk uezd according to the 1897 Russian Census|publisher=beljews.info|date=|accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Inter-war period===\n[[File:Kojdana\u016d. \u041a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u045e (1932).jpg|thumb|The People's House in Dzyarzhynsk, capital of the ''Dzier\u017cy\u0144szczyzna'', in 1932]]\nIn May 1932 it was granted the status of a city and was renamed '''Kojdana\u016d''' ({{lang-be|\u041a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u045e}}), Russian: '''Koidanov'''.  In June of that year it was renamed again as Dziar\u017eynsk by the [[Communism|Communist]] authorities, in honour of [[Felix Dzerzhinsky]] (1877\u20131926), a famous Bolshevik creator and chief of the \"Cherezzychainaya Komissija\" ([[CHEKA]]) \u2013 the Soviet secret police - who was born in a Dziar\u017eynava estate not far from the city, although on the other side of the then Polish-Soviet border.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>\n\nThe city was the capital of the short-lived [[Dzierzynszczyzna]] [[Polish Autonomous District]] during 1932\u201338.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>\n\n===World War II===\nIt fell under [[Operation Barbarossa|German occupation]] during World War II. It was captured on June 28, 1941.\n\nThe [[Lithuania]]n Twelfth [[Schutzmannschaft]] (auxiliary police) Battalion's 1st Company, led by Lieutenant Z. Kemzura, massacred approximately 1,600 Jews from the city on October 21, 1941, shooting them and throwing them into a pit; many were buried alive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jhrgbelarus.org/Heritage_Holocaust.php?pid=&lang=en&city_id=8&type=3|title=Jewish Heritage Research Group in Belarus|publisher=Jhrgbelarus.org|date=October 21, 1941|accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Richard|last=Breitman|authorlink=Richard Breitman|url=https://motlc.wiesenthal.com/site/pp.asp?c=gvKVLcMVIuG&b=395183|title=Himmler's Police Auxiliaries in the Occupied Soviet Territories|publisher=Simon Wiesenthal Center Multimedia Learning Center|date=1997|accessdate=August 20, 2011|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727011820/http://motlc.wiesenthal.com/site/pp.asp?c=gvKVLcMVIuG&b=395183|archivedate=July 27, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"google1941\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wvyX6Vjkq3MC&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=Koidanov+1941+-mascot#PPA155,M1 |title=The Complete Black Book of Russian Jewry |publisher= |author= |date=June 13, 2003 |accessdate=August 20, 2011|isbn=9781412820073 |author1=Patterson |first1=David }}</ref>  As it is reported in ''The Complete Black Book of Russian Jewry'': \"For three hours the earth covering the mass grave would move; people still alive were trying to crawl out of their grave.\"<ref name=\"google1941\"/>  On March 1\u20132,1942, the [[Einsatzgruppen]] transported several thousand Jews from throughout Belarussia and murdered them in Koidanov.<ref>{{cite book |author=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |title=Historical Atlas of the Holocaust |publisher=Macmillan / Simon & Schuster |date=1995 |isbn=978-0028974514 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/historicalatlaso00unit }} See in [https://www.rtrfoundation.org/map11a.shtml Routes to Roots Foundation, Inc.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821104558/https://www.rtrfoundation.org/map11a.shtml |date=August 21, 2016 }}</ref> The city was liberated by the Soviet [[Red Army]] on July 6, 1944.<ref name=\"beljews1\"/>\n\n===Modern day===\n[[File:Dzrerzhinsk Minsk oblast ulica Sovetskaja.jpg|thumb|Shopping centre in Dzyarzhynsk]]\n\nIn 1998, the city had 24,700 inhabitants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.populstat.info/Europe/belarust.htm |title=BELARUS: urban population |publisher=Populstat.info |date= |accessdate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNow part of Belarus, the name Kojdanava ({{lang-be|\u041a\u043e\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0430}}) is becoming popular again (it is the official name for the [[railway station]] of Dziarzhynsk), but the official name remains unchanged.\n\n==Geography==\nThe highest point of Belarus, [[Dziar\u017eynskaja Hara]], is several kilometers from Dziar\u017eynsk.\n\n== Transport ==\nThere is a railway road across the city from [[Minsk Railway station|Minsk Passazhirsky]] to Baranovichi Polesskie.\n\nThere is only one bus route in Dziarzhynsk, that has 18 stops.\n\n==Notable residents==\n* \n*[[Avrom Reyzen]] (1876\u20131953), Yiddish writer, poet, and editor\n*[[Aharon Perlow of Koidanov|Aharon Perlow]] (1839&ndash;1897) &ndash; third [[rebbe]] of [[Koidanov (Hasidic dynasty)|Koidanov]]\n*[[Karol Hutten-Czapski]], [[Leliwa coat of arms]], (1860-1904).  [[Poles|Polish]] [[Count]] and philanthropist. President of [[Minsk]], [[Lithuania]] (1890-1901)\n*[[Emeryk Hutten-Czapski]], [[Leliwa coat of arms]], (1828\u20131896).  [[Poland|Polish]] [[Count]], scholar, ardent historical collector and [[numismatist]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Dziar\u017eynsk}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040402171314/http://www.dzerzhinsk.boom.ru/aboutme.html Dzerzhinsk (in Russian)]\n* [http://www.radzima.org/eng/town/dzyarzhynsk-koydanava.html Photos on Radzima.org]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050221025912/http://uk.multimap.com/wi/337941.htm Map of Dziar\u017eynsk]\n\n\n{{Minsk Voblast}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Minsk Region]]\n[[Category:Dzyarzhynsk District]]\n[[Category:Minsk Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Minsky Uyezd]]\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dzyarzhynsk"}
{"title_page": "Boana", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Gladiator frog Osa.JPG\n| image_caption = ''[[Boana rosenbergi]]''\n| taxon = Boana\n| authority = [[John Edward Gray|Gray]], 1825\n| type_species = ''[[Boana boans|Rana boans]]''\n| type_species_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| diversity = About 90 species (see [[#Species|text]])\n| synonyms = {{hidden begin|title = List}}\n* ''Hysaplesia'' <small>Boie ''in Schlegel'', 1826</small>\n* ''Hypsiboas'' <small>[[Johann Georg Wagler|Wagler]], 1830</small>\n* ''Auletris'' <small>Wagler, 1830</small>\n* ''Lobipes'' <small>Fitzinger, 1843</small>\n* ''Hypsipsophus'' <small>Fitzinger, 1843</small>\n* ''Phyllobius'' <small>Fitzinger, 1843</small>\n* ''Centrotelma'' <small>Burmeister, 1856</small>\n* ''Hylomedusa'' <small>Burmeister, 1856</small>\n* ''Cinclidium'' <small>Cope, 1867</small>\n* ''Cophomantis'' <small>Peters, 1870</small>\n* ''Cincloscopus'' <small>Cope, 1871</small>\n{{hidden end}}\n}}\n\n'''''Boana''''' is a genus of [[frog]]s in the family [[Hylidae]]. They are commonly known as '''gladiator frogs''', '''gladiator treefrogs''' or '''Wagler Neotropical treefrogs'''. These frogs are distributed in the tropical Central and South America from Nicaragua to Argentina, as well as in the Caribbean (Trinidad and Tobago).<ref name=frost>{{cite web |url=https://amphibiansoftheworld.amnh.org/Amphibia/Anura/Hylidae/Cophomantinae/Boana |title=''Boana'' Gray, 1825 |author=Frost, Darrel R. |year=2020 |work=Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference. Version 6.1 |publisher=American Museum of Natural History |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis genus was resurrected following a major revision of Hylidae when some 70 species previously placed in the genus ''[[Hyla]]'' were moved to this genus. Since then, many new species have also been described.<ref name=frost/><ref name=\"Faivovich\">{{cite journal|author1=Juli\u00e1n Faivovich |author2=C\u00e9lio F.B. Haddad |author3=Paulo C.A. Garcia |author4=Darrel R. Frost |author5=Jonathan A. Campbell |author6=Ward C. Wheeler |year=2005|title=Systematic review of the frog family Hylidae, with special reference to Hylinae: phylogenetic analysis and taxonomic revision|journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History|volume=294|pages=1\u2013240|doi=10.1206/0003-0090(2005)294[0001:SROTFF]2.0.CO;2|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/handle/2246/462|citeseerx=10.1.1.470.2967 }}</ref>\n\n==Species==\nAs of April, 2020, there are 95 species recognised in this genus:<ref name=frost/>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[Boana aguilari]]'' <small>Lehr, Faivovich, and Jungfer, 2010</small>\n* ''[[Boana albomarginata]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 white-edged tree frog\n* ''[[Boana albonigra]]'' <small>(Nieden, 1923)</small> \u2013 white-black tree frog\n* ''[[Boana albopunctata]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 white-spotted tree frog\n* ''[[Boana alemani]]'' <small>(Rivero, 1964)</small> \u2013 Cagua tree frog\n* ''[[Boana alfaroi]]'' <small>Caminer and Ron, 2014</small>\n* ''[[Boana almendarizae]]'' <small>Caminer and Ron, 2014</small>\n* ''[[Boana appendiculata]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1882)</small>\n* ''[[Boana atlantica]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Velosa, 1996)</small>\n* ''[[Boana balzani]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1898)</small> \u2013 Yungas tree frog\n* ''[[Boana bandeirantes]]'' <small>Caramaschi and Cruz, 2013</small>\n* ''[[Boana beckeri]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 2004)</small>\n* ''[[Boana benitezi]]'' <small>(Rivero, 1961)</small> \u2013 Benitez's tree frog\n* ''[[Boana bischoffi]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1887)</small> \u2013 Bischoff's tree frog\n* ''[[Boana boans]]'' <small>([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])</small> \u2013 rusty tree frog\n* ''[[Boana botumirim]]'' <small>(Caramaschi, Cruz, and Nascimento, 2009)</small>\n* ''[[Boana buriti]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 1999)</small>\n* ''[[Boana caiapo]]'' <small>Pinheiro, Cintra, Valdujo, Silva, Martins, Silva, and Garcia, 2018</small>\n* ''[[Boana caingua]]'' <small>(Carrizo, 1991)</small> \u2013 striped tree frog\n* ''[[Boana caipora]]'' <small>(Antunes, Faivovich, and Haddad, 2008)</small>\n* ''[[Boana calcarata]]'' <small>(Troschel, 1848)</small> \u2013 Troschel's tree frog or, convict tree frog\n* ''[[Boana callipleura]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1902)</small> \u2013 Charuplaya tree frog\n* ''[[Boana cambui]]'' <small>(Pinheiro, Pezzuti, Leite, Garcia, Haddad, and Faivovich, 2016)</small>\n* ''[[Boana cinerascens]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 Demerara Falls tree frog\n* ''[[Boana cipoensis]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1968)</small>\n* ''[[Boana cordobae]]'' <small>(Barrio, 1965)</small>\n* ''[[Boana crepitans]]'' <small>(Wied-Neuwied, 1824)</small> \u2013 emerald-eyed tree frog\n* ''[[Boana curupi]]'' <small>(Garcia, Faivovich, and Haddad, 2007)</small>\n* ''[[Boana cymbalum]]'' <small>(Bokermann, 1963)</small> \u2013 Campo Grande tree frog\n* ''[[Boana dentei]]'' <small>(Bokermann, 1967)</small> \u2013 Amapa tree frog\n* ''[[Boana diabolica]]'' <small>(Fouquet ''et al''., 2016)</small>\n* ''[[Boana ericae]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 2000)</small>\n* ''[[Boana exastis]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Rodrigues, 2003)</small>\n* ''[[Boana faber]]'' <small>(Wied-Neuwied, 1821)</small> \u2013 blacksmith tree frog\n* ''[[Boana fasciata]]'' <small>(G\u00fcnther, 1858)</small> \u2013 Gunther's banded tree frog\n* ''[[Boana freicanecae]]'' <small>(Carnaval and Peixoto, 2004)</small>\n* ''[[Boana fuentei]]'' <small>(Goin and Goin, 1968)</small> \u2013 Fuente's Powakka tree frog\n* ''[[Boana geographica]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 map tree frog\n* ''[[Boana gladiator]]'' <small>(K\u00f6hler''et al''., 2010)</small>\n* ''[[Boana goiana]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1968)</small>\n* ''[[Boana guentheri]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1886)</small> \u2013 Gunther's Brazilian tree frog\n* ''[[Boana heilprini]]'' <small>(Noble, 1923)</small> \u2013 Los Bracitos tree frog\n* ''[[Boana hobbsi]]'' <small>(Cochran and Goin, 1970)</small> \u2013 Hobbs' tree frog\n* ''[[Boana hutchinsi]]'' <small>(Pyburn and Hall, 1984)</small> \u2013 Hutchins' tree frog\n* ''[[Boana icamiaba]]'' <small>Peloso''et al''., 2018</small>\n* ''[[Boana jaguariaivensis]]'' <small>Caramaschi, Cruz, and Segalla, 2010</small>\n* ''[[Boana jimenezi]]'' <small>Se\u00f1aris and Ayarzag\u00fcena, 2006</small>\n* ''[[Boana joaquini]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1968)</small>\n* ''[[Boana lanciformis]]'' <small>(Cope, 1871)</small> \u2013 basin tree frog\n* ''[[Boana latistriata]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 2004)</small>\n* ''[[Boana lemai]]'' <small>(Rivero, 1972)</small> \u2013 Lema tree frog\n* ''[[Boana leptolineata]]'' <small>(Braun and Braun, 1977)</small> \u2013 fine-lined tree frog\n* ''[[Boana leucocheila]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Niemeyer, 2003)</small>\n* ''[[Boana lundii]]'' <small>(Burmeister, 1856)</small> \u2013 Usina tree frog\n* ''[[Boana maculateralis]]'' <small>(Caminer and Ron, 2014)</small>\n* ''[[Boana marginata]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1887)</small> \u2013 Mundo Novo tree frog\n* ''[[Boana marianitae]]'' <small>(Carrizo, 1992)</small> \u2013 Salta tree frog\n* ''[[Boana melanopleura]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1912)</small> \u2013 Lower Andes tree frog\n* ''[[Boana microderma]]'' <small>(Pyburn, 1977)</small> \u2013 smallskin tree frog\n* ''[[Boana multifasciata]]'' <small>(G\u00fcnther, 1859)</small> \u2013 many-banded tree frog\n* ''[[Boana nigra]]'' <small>Caminer and Ron, 2020</small>\n* ''[[Boana nympha]]'' <small>(Faivovich, Moravec, Cisneros-Heredia, and K\u00f6hler, 2006)</small>\n* ''[[Boana ornatissima]]'' <small>(Noble, 1923)</small> \u2013 ornate tree frog\n* ''[[Boana palaestes]]'' <small>(Duellman, De la Riva, and Wild, 1997)</small>\n* ''[[Boana paranaiba]]'' <small>Carvalho and Giaretta, 2010</small>\n* ''[[Boana pardalis]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 leopard tree frog\n* ''[[Boana pellucens]]'' <small>(Werner, 1901)</small> \u2013 palmar tree frog \n* ''[[Boana phaeopleura]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 2000)</small>\n* ''[[Boana picturata]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1899)</small> \u2013 Imbabura tree frog\n* ''[[Boana poaju]]'' <small>(Garcia, Peixoto, and Haddad, 2008)</small>\n* ''[[Boana polytaenia]]'' <small>(Cope, 1870)</small> \u2013 Cope's eastern Paraguay tree frog\n* ''[[Boana pombali]]'' <small>(Caramaschi, Pimenta, and Feio, 2004)</small>\n* ''[[Boana prasina]]'' <small>(Burmeister, 1856)</small> \u2013 Burmeister's tree frog\n* ''[[Boana pugnax]]'' <small>(Schmidt, 1857)</small> \u2013 Chirique-Flusse tree frog\n* ''[[Boana pulchella]]'' <small>(Dum\u00e9ril and Bibron, 1841)</small> \u2013 Montevideo tree frog\n* ''[[Boana punctata]]'' <small>(Schneider, 1799)</small> \u2013 polka-dot tree frog\n* ''[[Boana raniceps]]'' <small>(Cope, 1862)</small> \u2013 Chaco tree frog\n* ''[[Boana rhythmica]]'' <small>(Se\u00f1aris and Ayarzag\u00fcena, 2002)</small>\n* ''[[Boana riojana]]'' <small>(Koslowsky, 1895)</small>\n* ''[[Boana roraima]]'' <small>(Duellman and Hoogmoed, 1992)</small> \u2013 Hoogmoed's tree frog\n* ''[[Boana rosenbergi]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1898)</small> \u2013 Rosenberg's tree frog\n* ''[[Boana rubracyla]]'' <small>(Cochran and Goin, 1970)</small> \u2013 Valle tree frog\n* ''[[Boana rufitela]]'' <small>(Fouquette, 1961)</small> \u2013 Canal Zone tree frog\n* ''[[Boana secedens]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1963)</small> \u2013 Barro Branco tree frog\n* ''[[Boana semiguttata]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1925)</small> \u2013 speckled tree frog\n* ''[[Boana semilineata]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small>\n* ''[[Boana sibleszi]]'' <small>(Rivero, 1972)</small> \u2013 La Escalera tree frog\n* ''[[Boana steinbachi]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1905)</small>\n* ''[[Boana stellae]]'' <small>(Kwet, 2008)</small>\n* ''[[Boana stenocephala]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 1999)</small>\n* ''[[Boana tepuiana]]'' <small>(Barrio-Amor\u00f3s and Brewer-Carias, 2008)</small>\n* ''[[Boana tetete]]'' <small>(Caminer and Ron, 2014)</small>\n* ''[[Boana ventrimaculata]]'' <small>Caminer and Ron, 2014</small>\n* ''[[Boana wavrini]]'' <small>(Parker, 1936)</small> \u2013 Upper Orinoco tree frog\n* ''[[Boana xerophylla]]'' <small>(Dum\u00e9ril and Bibron, 1841)</small>\n}}\n\nIn addition, ''[[Hyla palliata]]'' and ''[[Hypsiboas hypselops]]'' are included here as ''[[incertae sedis]]''.<ref name=frost/>\n\n==References==<!-- Zootaxa1927:1. -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q580558|from2=Q39384115}}\n\n[[Category:Hylinae]]\n[[Category:Boana| ]]\n[[Category:Amphibian genera]]\n[[Category:Amphibians of the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Amphibians of Central America]]\n[[Category:Amphibians of South America]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Edward Gray]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Gladiator frog Osa.JPG\n| image_caption = ''[[Boana rosenbergi]]''\n| taxon = Boana\n| authority = [[John Edward Gray|Gray]], 1825\n| type_species = ''[[Boana boans|Rana boans]]''\n| type_species_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| diversity = About 90 species (see [[#Species|text]])\n| synonyms = {{hidden begin|title = List}}\n* ''Hysaplesia'' <small>Boie ''in Schlegel'', 1826</small>\n* ''Hypsiboas'' <small>[[Johann Georg Wagler|Wagler]], 1830</small>\n* ''Auletris'' <small>Wagler, 1830</small>\n* ''Lobipes'' <small>Fitzinger, 1843</small>\n* ''Hypsipsophus'' <small>Fitzinger, 1843</small>\n* ''Phyllobius'' <small>Fitzinger, 1843</small>\n* ''Centrotelma'' <small>Burmeister, 1856</small>\n* ''Hylomedusa'' <small>Burmeister, 1856</small>\n* ''Cinclidium'' <small>Cope, 1867</small>\n* ''Cophomantis'' <small>Peters, 1870</small>\n* ''Cincloscopus'' <small>Cope, 1871</small>\n{{hidden end}}\n}}\n\n'''''Boana''''' is a genus of [[frog]]s in the family [[Hylidae]]. They are commonly known as '''gladiator frogs''', '''gladiator treefrogs''' or '''Wagler Neotropical treefrogs'''. These frogs are distributed in the tropical Central and South America from Nicaragua to Argentina, as well as in the Caribbean (Trinidad and Tobago).<ref name=frost>{{cite web |url=https://amphibiansoftheworld.amnh.org/Amphibia/Anura/Hylidae/Cophomantinae/Boana |title=''Boana'' Gray, 1825 |author=Frost, Darrel R. |year=2020 |work=Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference. Version 6.1 |publisher=American Museum of Natural History |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis genus was resurrected following a major revision of Hylidae when some 70 species previously placed in the genus ''[[Hyla]]'' were moved to this genus. Since then, many new species have also been described.<ref name=frost/><ref name=\"Faivovich\">{{cite journal|author1=Juli\u00e1n Faivovich |author2=C\u00e9lio F.B. Haddad |author3=Paulo C.A. Garcia |author4=Darrel R. Frost |author5=Jonathan A. Campbell |author6=Ward C. Wheeler |year=2005|title=Systematic review of the frog family Hylidae, with special reference to Hylinae: phylogenetic analysis and taxonomic revision|journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History|volume=294|pages=1\u2013240|doi=10.1206/0003-0090(2005)294[0001:SROTFF]2.0.CO;2|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/handle/2246/462|citeseerx=10.1.1.470.2967 }}</ref>\n\n==Species==\nAs of April, 2020, there are 95 species recognised in this genus:<ref name=frost/>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[Boana aguilari]]'' <small>Lehr, Faivovich, and Jungfer, 2010</small>\n* ''[[Boana albomarginata]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 white-edged tree frog\n* ''[[Boana albonigra]]'' <small>(Nieden, 1923)</small> \u2013 white-black tree frog\n* ''[[Boana albopunctata]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 white-spotted tree frog\n* ''[[Boana alemani]]'' <small>(Rivero, 1964)</small> \u2013 Cagua tree frog\n* ''[[Boana alfaroi]]'' <small>Caminer and Ron, 2014</small>\n* ''[[Boana almendarizae]]'' <small>Caminer and Ron, 2014</small>\n* ''[[Boana appendiculata]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1882)</small>\n* ''[[Boana atlantica]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Velosa, 1996)</small>\n* ''[[Boana balzani]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1898)</small> \u2013 Yungas tree frog\n* ''[[Boana bandeirantes]]'' <small>Caramaschi and Cruz, 2013</small>\n* ''[[Boana beckeri]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 2004)</small>\n* ''[[Boana benitezi]]'' <small>(Rivero, 1961)</small> \u2013 Benitez's tree frog\n* ''[[Boana bischoffi]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1887)</small> \u2013 Bischoff's tree frog\n* ''[[Boana boans]]'' <small>([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])</small> \u2013 rusty tree frog\n* ''[[Boana botumirim]]'' <small>(Caramaschi, Cruz, and Nascimento, 2009)</small>\n* ''[[Boana buriti]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 1999)</small>\n* ''[[Boana caiapo]]'' <small>Pinheiro, Cintra, Valdujo, Silva, Martins, Silva, and Garcia, 2018</small>\n* ''[[Boana caingua]]'' <small>(Carrizo, 1991)</small> \u2013 striped tree frog\n* ''[[Boana caipora]]'' <small>(Antunes, Faivovich, and Haddad, 2008)</small>\n* ''[[Boana calcarata]]'' <small>(Troschel, 1848)</small> \u2013 Troschel's tree frog or, convict tree frog\n* ''[[Boana callipleura]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1902)</small> \u2013 Charuplaya tree frog\n* ''[[Boana cambui]]'' <small>(Pinheiro, Pezzuti, Leite, Garcia, Haddad, and Faivovich, 2016)</small>\n* ''[[Boana cinerascens]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 Demerara Falls tree frog\n* ''[[Boana cipoensis]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1968)</small>\n* ''[[Boana cordobae]]'' <small>(Barrio, 1965)</small>\n* ''[[Boana crepitans]]'' <small>(Wied-Neuwied, 1824)</small> \u2013 emerald-eyed tree frog\n* ''[[Boana curupi]]'' <small>(Garcia, Faivovich, and Haddad, 2007)</small>\n* ''[[Boana cymbalum]]'' <small>(Bokermann, 1963)</small> \u2013 Campo Grande tree frog\n* ''[[Boana dentei]]'' <small>(Bokermann, 1967)</small> \u2013 Amapa tree frog\n* ''[[Boana diabolica]]'' <small>(Fouquet ''et al''., 2016)</small>\n* ''[[Boana ericae]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 2000)</small>\n* ''[[Boana exastis]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Rodrigues, 2003)</small>\n* ''[[Boana faber]]'' <small>(Wied-Neuwied, 1821)</small> \u2013 blacksmith tree frog\n* ''[[Boana fasciata]]'' <small>(G\u00fcnther, 1858)</small> \u2013 Gunther's banded tree frog\n* ''[[Boana freicanecae]]'' <small>(Carnaval and Peixoto, 2004)</small>\n* ''[[Boana fuentei]]'' <small>(Goin and Goin, 1968)</small> \u2013 Fuente's Powakka tree frog\n* ''[[Boana geographica]]'' <small>(Spix, 1824)</small> \u2013 map tree frog\n* ''[[Boana gladiator]]'' <small>(K\u00f6hler''et al''., 2010)</small>\n* ''[[Boana goiana]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1968)</small>\n* ''[[Boana guentheri]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1886)</small> \u2013 Gunther's Brazilian tree frog\n* ''[[Boana heilprini]]'' <small>(Noble, 1923)</small> \u2013 Los Bracitos tree frog\n* ''[[Boana hobbsi]]'' <small>(Cochran and Goin, 1970)</small> \u2013 Hobbs' tree frog\n* ''[[Boana hutchinsi]]'' <small>(Pyburn and Hall, 1984)</small> \u2013 Hutchins' tree frog\n* ''[[Boana icamiaba]]'' <small>Peloso''et al''., 2018</small>\n* ''[[Boana jaguariaivensis]]'' <small>Caramaschi, Cruz, and Segalla, 2010</small>\n* ''[[Boana jimenezi]]'' <small>Se\u00f1aris and Ayarzag\u00fcena, 2006</small>\n* ''[[Boana joaquini]]'' <small>(Lutz, 1968)</small>\n* ''[[Boana lanciformis]]'' <small>(Cope, 1871)</small> \u2013 basin tree frog\n* ''[[Boana latistriata]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Cruz, 2004)</small>\n* ''[[Boana lemai]]'' <small>(Rivero, 1972)</small> \u2013 Lema tree frog\n* ''[[Boana leptolineata]]'' <small>(Braun and Braun, 1977)</small> \u2013 fine-lined tree frog\n* ''[[Boana leucocheila]]'' <small>(Caramaschi and Niemeyer, 2003)</small>\n* ''[[Boana lundii]]'' <small>(Burmeister, 1856)</small> \u2013 Usina tree frog\n* ''[[Boana maculateralis]]'' <small>(Caminer and Ron, 2014)</small>\n* ''[[Boana marginata]]'' <small>(Boulenger, 1887)</small> \u2013 Mundo Novo tree frog\n* ''[[Boana marianitae]]'' <small>(Carrizo, 1992)</small> \u2013 Salta 